'''Syndell Studio''' was an [[art gallery]] located in the [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]] neighborhood of [[Los Angeles]], California, between 1954 and 1956.
==History== Syndell Studio was founded in 1954 by [[Walter Hopps]] and [[Jim Newman (television producer)|Jim Newman]], with Michael Scoles, poet Ben Bartosh and his wife Betty Brunt. It was located at 11756 Gorham Avenue, Brentwood, in a (no longer extant) building constructed from used pier pilings and remnants from a demolished [[Santa Monica]] beach club.<ref name=brad>{{cite journal|last1=Bradnock|first1=Lucy|title=Walter Hopps's Los Angeles Pastoral|journal=Art Journal|date=2012|volume=71|issue=1}}</ref> According to oral history interviews with Hopps, Newman, and artist [[Edward Kienholz]], the gallery was named after Maurice Sindel, a Midwestern farmer who died on the highway in Ohio on 6 June 1953.<ref name=Peabody>{{cite book|last1=Peabody|first1=Rebecca et al. (eds)|title=Pacific Standard Time: Los Angeles Art, 1945-80|date=2011|publisher=Getty|location=Los Angeles|page=75}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ohio Department of Health|title=Certificate of Death|journal=Ohio Historical Society|pages=state file no. 42714}}</ref> The accident was witnessed by Newman as he drove from [[Oberlin, Ohio|Oberlin]] to Los Angeles. Hopps stated, "It's just too absurd, that this man dies in obscurity. We're going to make him an artist. We're going to create work for him. We're going to put him in group shows. We're going to name our place after him, as though it had been his studio".<ref name=brad/>
The gallery's business cards were created by poet and printmaker Robert Alexander. Alexander and [[Wallace Berman]] designed invitations to exhibitions.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}
==Exhibitions== On 21 October 1956, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' art critic [[Jules Langsner]] wrote, "For a glimpse of avant-garde art in Los Angeles, the place to go is Syndell Studios".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Langsner|first1=Jules|authorlink=Jules Langser|title=Association Opens Show of 'Human Figure in Art'|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=October 21, 1956|page=D6}}</ref>
Exhibitions held at Syndell Studio included: * Children's Art from Southern California Nursery Schools, August–September 1955<ref name=brad/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Anon.|title=Art Events This Week|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=11 September 1955|page=D7}}</ref> * [[Edward Kienholz]] wooden constructions * Arthur Richer paintings, 1956<ref>{{cite web|last1=Getty Research Institute|title=Syndell Studio|url=http://blogs.getty.edu/pacificstandardtime/explore-the-era/locations/syndell-studio/|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref> * [[Sonia Gechtoff]], 1956<ref>{{cite book|title=Flier for exhibition of work by Sonia Gechtoff, Syndell Studio, 1956|publisher=Los Angeles, Getty Research Institute|location= collection 2005.M.11}}</ref>
In 1955 Syndell Studio co-organised with Gallery 6, San Francisco, the exhibition ''Action'' of abstract painting, which was held at the merry-go-round building on [[Santa Monica Pier]].<ref>Peabody (2011), pp. 63-68.</ref> Syndell also co-organised the follow-up ''Action2'' (''Action Squared'') exhibition, held in 1956 at Edward Kienholz's [[Now Gallery]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Allan|first1=Ken|title=Creating an avant-garde in 1950s Los Angeles: Robert Alexander's hand-printed gallery brochure in the Archives of American Art|journal=Archives of American Art Journal|date=2002|volume=42|issue=3-4|pages=21–26}}</ref> In 1956, Syndell Studio was featured in the Los Angeles All-City Outdoor Art Festival at [[Barnsdall Art Park|Barnsdall Park]].
